      <title>President-elect Trump asks Senate to take a recess</title>
      <author>Joshua Tauberer       </author>
      <link>https://www.govtrack.us/posts/453/2024-11-11_president-elect-trump-asks-senate-to-take-a-recess</link>
      <guid isPermaLink="true">https://www.govtrack.us/posts/453/2024-11-11_president-elect-trump-asks-senate-to-take-a-recess</guid>
      <pubDate>Mon, 11 Nov 2024 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <description>                &lt;p&gt;We're back. And it's a little sooner than we expected.  President-elect Trump put his thumb on incoming Republican senators' leadership elections over the weekend by &lt;a href="https://x.com/realDonaldTrump/status/1855692242981155259"&gt;demanding&lt;/a&gt; that the Senate allow "recess appointments" next year. He wants to get around the Constitution's checks and balances that gives the Senate its role in confirming nominees. Here's why, and some other ways Trump could do it.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;h3&gt;Recess appointments have been essentially defunct for more than a decade&lt;/h3&gt; &lt;p&gt;Normally the President nominates and then the Senate confirms top government positions including &lt;a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_positions_filled_by_presidential_appointment_with_Senate_confirmation"&gt;more than 1,000 agency heads and senior officers&lt;/a&gt;, senior military officers including generals, as well as judges and Supreme Court justices. But there was a workaround: &lt;a href="https://constitution.congress.gov/browse/article-2/section-2/clause-3/"&gt;Article II, section 2, clause 3 of the Constitution&lt;/a&gt; gives the President the power to make temporary appointments when the Senate is out of session for &lt;a href="https://www.everycrsreport.com/reports/RS21308.html"&gt;at least ten days&lt;/a&gt;, called &lt;a href="https://www.everycrsreport.com/reports/RS21308.html"&gt;recess appointments&lt;/a&gt;. These appointments last for &lt;a href="https://www.everycrsreport.com/reports/RS21308.html#fn38"&gt;at most two years&lt;/a&gt;. The President can seek confirmation of the appointee to make it permanent, or not, and there are some laws that limit paying certain recess appointees to discourage doing it.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;In the first 100 years of the country, the recess appointment power made sense: the Senate was &lt;a href="https://www.everycrsreport.com/reports/RS21308.html"&gt;out of session more than it was in session&lt;/a&gt;. In modern times, recess appointments had been a way for the President to use the Senate's short breaks to work around senators withholding their "advice and consent."&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;But the recess appointment power has been essentially defunct for more than a decade now (&lt;a href="https://x.com/danielschuman/status/1855787305958621264"&gt;here's a chart&lt;/a&gt;). In 2011 the Senate simply stopped going into recess to prevent recess appointments, and &lt;a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/NLRB_v._Noel_Canning"&gt;in 2014 the Supreme Court upheld the Senate's practice&lt;/a&gt; after President Obama made recess appointments anyway. The last recess appointment seems to have been &lt;a href="https://sgp.fas.org/crs/misc/R42329.pdf"&gt;in 2010&lt;/a&gt; (excluding the ones vacated in the 2014 ruling). Trump tried &lt;a href="https://www.vox.com/2020/4/16/21223488/trump-adjourn-congress-recess-appointment-constitution-mitch-mcconnell"&gt;to use this power back in 2020&lt;/a&gt; but, as far as I can tell, he didn't have the opportunity to do so because the Senate remained in session.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Over long holidays and other times when senators aren't expected to be working at the Capitol (like the last few weeks), one senator gavels in and gavels out every few days so that the time off isn't legally a recess. No recess, no recess appointment. These "pro forma" sessions have now long been standard practice.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Trump is asking the Senate to voluntarily go on a break without pro forma sessions for the 10 days long enough to be considered in recess, and the House would need to agree. If Congress chooses to abrogate one of its Constitutional duties, that would be concerning.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;h3&gt;Why Trump may be asking&lt;/h3&gt; &lt;p&gt;There are three reasons Trump may be thinking about it again. "Sometimes the votes can take two years, or more," Trump wrote on X last weekend, which is true: Vetting a nominee, holding a hearing, and making floor time for a vote can take time and hold up a President's agenda. It is often too slow. But the process is the point: It's a check on unqualified nominees.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;But it doesn't take long if senators want to move fast. In Trump's first term, his Defense and Homeland Security Secretaries were confirmed the same day Trump took office, thanks to Senate leg-work that was finished before Inauguration Day, but &lt;a href="https://www.cnn.com/2017/02/25/politics/donald-trump-cabinet-vacancies/index.html"&gt;the Senate held back others&lt;/a&gt;. Sometimes senators drag it out: Senate tradition allows any senator to request a "hold," such as when Sen. Tuberville (R) &lt;a href="https://www.militarytimes.com/news/pentagon-congress/2023/12/06/here-are-the-425-military-leaders-finally-confirmed-by-the-senate/"&gt;held the nomination of 400 military officers for 10 months&lt;/a&gt; last year over a largely unrelated policy dispute.  Recess appointments could accelerate policy changes in Trump's first year.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Trump may also be hoping to appoint officials that he thinks may not get enough support in the Senate for confirmation. Although Republicans will hold 52 to 54 seats in the Senate, only 50 is needed for confirmation (with soon-to-be Vice President Vance casting a tie-breaking vote). But senators don't always fall in line. Recess appointments would get around needing a Senate vote. (The 60-vote filibuster or "cloture" threshold doesn't apply here. Since 2013, the threshold for nominations has been a simple majority. Democrats dropped the higher threshold for nominations that year to get around Republican no's.)&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Lastly, Trump's would-be nominees may not want to go through the Senate's normally rigorous vetting process, background checks, and public hearings in order to keep their personal life and business dealings out of the public eye.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;h3&gt;What could happen&lt;/h3&gt; &lt;p&gt;The Senate could choose to go into recess, if the House agrees. A recess intended to abrogate a Constitutional duty would be very concerning, however. It would remove an important check on presidential power and let senators green-light appointments without being on the record voting for them, but that might be the point. If there are enough legislators in both chambers voting in favor of a recess (both chambers must agree), then there are probably enough senators to confirm the nomination anyway. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The President &lt;a href="https://www.vox.com/2020/4/16/21223488/trump-adjourn-congress-recess-appointment-constitution-mitch-mcconnell"&gt;can't force the Senate into recess&lt;/a&gt;, although maybe the President and the House can together. That would be even more concerning. It's never happened.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;The Senate could also change its norms by holding closed hearings to skip public vettings of nominees, they could confirm more nominees without a record of how each senator votes (which they do for many &lt;a href="https://www.everycrsreport.com/reports/RS20986.html"&gt;noncontroversial&lt;/a&gt; non-political nominations), or, better, they could find a way to vet nominees faster.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;There are some alternatives for the President: Trump could &lt;a href="https://www.everycrsreport.com/reports/R40119.html"&gt;use the Vacancies Reform Act to fill these roles temporarily&lt;/a&gt; by promoting top civil servants that support his policies. That's the best option for a temporary appointment. Congress may find some positions to give the President power to appoint without Senate consent (but the Constitution requires top decision-makers be Senate-confirmed), and they may also repeal those &lt;a href="https://www.everycrsreport.com/reports/RS21308.html"&gt;statutory limits on paying recess appointees&lt;/a&gt;. He could also simply leave these positions vacant to hamstring agencies that don't follow his agenda.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;For a list of Senate-confirmed positions in the civil service, &lt;a href="https://www.opm.gov/about-us/open-government/plum-reporting/plum-data/"&gt;search the PLUM Data&lt;/a&gt; for "PAS" appointments.&lt;/p&gt;      </description>
      <category>&amp;middot; Analysis and Commentary 	&amp;middot; by Joshua Tauberer 	</category>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>What To Expect, And What Not, on Election Day and in the Weeks Ahead</title>
      <author>Joshua Tauberer       </author>
      <link>https://www.govtrack.us/posts/451/2024-10-31_what-to-expect-and-what-not-on-election-day-and-in-the-weeks-ahead</link>
      <guid isPermaLink="true">https://www.govtrack.us/posts/451/2024-10-31_what-to-expect-and-what-not-on-election-day-and-in-the-weeks-ahead</guid>
      <pubDate>Thu, 31 Oct 2024 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <description>                &lt;p&gt;The period between Election Day and when all the results are final can be, let's say, a little bumpy. Some things are an expected part of what it means to have free and fair elections. But some are not.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Here are some principles to sort out what's normal and what's not normal:&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;Normal&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;ul&gt; &lt;li&gt; &lt;p&gt;Some media outlets will "call" races, but elections officials will still be counting all the ballots. Results come in piecemeal, and some states are faster than others. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;/li&gt; &lt;li&gt; &lt;p&gt;We expect candidates to use state and federal courts to resolve disputes about how to get to certified vote totals. This is the right way to do it.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;/li&gt; &lt;/ul&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;Not Normal&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;ul&gt; &lt;li&gt;But if clerks and other officials fail to certify a result or seek to select a winner based on something other than the total of all certified totals, that would &lt;em&gt;not&lt;/em&gt; be normal — or worse.&lt;/li&gt; &lt;/ul&gt; &lt;h3&gt;What to expect on Election Night and in the weeks after&lt;/h3&gt; &lt;p&gt;As the votes are counted, expect to see the earliest reports on Election Night based mostly on mail-in ballots, then some precinct-by-precinct in-person voting results will start to mix in. Only about half of the country's votes will be reported by midnight Eastern Time. Over days more mail-in ballots will be processed and added into the totals. The "winners" will seem to lurch back and forth as ballots are added in — it happens in every close election.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;In Utah, where since 2018 nearly all citizens have voted by mail, clerks &lt;a href="https://www.usnews.com/news/politics/articles/2024-10-25/ap-decision-notes-what-to-expect-in-utah-on-election-day"&gt;begin the counting before Election Day&lt;/a&gt; so their results are fairly fast. Similarly, you can see &lt;a href="https://escambiavotes.gov/docs/soelibraries/notices/legal-notice-canvassing-board-meetings-august-20-primary.pdf?sfvrsn=b16010f2_1"&gt;here&lt;/a&gt; that Florida began scanning mail-in ballots for its last primary election nearly a month before the election. But in Pennsylvania, the law is that mail-in ballots &lt;a href="https://www.usnews.com/news/politics/articles/2024-10-22/ap-decision-notes-what-to-expect-in-pennsylvania-on-election-day"&gt;can't be processed until Election Day&lt;/a&gt;, drawing out the timeline. In 2020, the Associated Press (AP) called the race for president in Pennsylvania on the Saturday morning after Election Day. Recounts in counties in four other states weren't complete until the end of the month — though &lt;a href="https://www.reuters.com/article/fact-check/contrary-to-social-media-posts-recounts-of-the-2020-us-presidential-election-idUSL2N2WJ1J9/"&gt;none flipped the winner&lt;/a&gt;. While AP waits for nearly all the votes to be in, most media outlets use statistics to predict sooner how the uncounted votes will go based on past precinct results.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Court challenges have already started, and that's a good thing. Judges in Georgia and Florida recently &lt;a href="https://www.cnn.com/2024/10/10/politics/georgia-florida-voter-registration-deadlines/index.html"&gt;ruled against left-aligned groups seeking to extend voter registration&lt;/a&gt; after the two disruptive hurricanes there, and a federal judge in North Carolina &lt;a href="https://www.wral.com/story/gop-officials-can-t-purge-225-000-voters-in-nc-trump-appointed-judge-rules/21678839/"&gt;ruled against the Republican Party seeking to remove 225,000 voter registrations&lt;/a&gt; that they claimed were illegal (but may not have been). In Pennsylvania, &lt;a href="https://www.justsecurity.org/104174/election-top-10-oct-23/"&gt;ongoing litigation&lt;/a&gt; is considering whether voters should be notified if their mail-in ballots are rejected. This is the time to resolve disputes, and courts are the place to do it.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Federal law recognizes that court challenges are an expected and welcome part of the process. The law gives states five weeks to count the votes for president and work through those court challenges. By December 11, &lt;a href="https://campaignlegal.org/sites/default/files/2024-09/ElectingthePresident_FromElectionDaytotheJointSession.pdf"&gt;states must send certified results&lt;/a&gt; of their presidential election — their slate of "electors" — to the federal government. The majority of electors determines the next president.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;h3&gt;Now to what's not normal.&lt;/h3&gt; &lt;p&gt;State officials must certify election results, but some elections officials throughout the country have been looking for ways to avoid reporting out the vote totals. In 2022, elections officials in North Carolina, Arizona, Nevada, Pennsylvania and New Mexico &lt;a href="https://www.propublica.org/article/election-officials-refused-certify-results-few-held-accountable"&gt;refused to certify election results&lt;/a&gt;, in some cases until a court ordered them to do so. This year, Georgia's elections board told its clerks to withhold certification until they perform an "inquiry," which the state's Supreme Court &lt;a href="https://www.justsecurity.org/104174/election-top-10-oct-23/"&gt;ruled&lt;/a&gt; went beyond state law. Elections officials must count up the votes quickly following their state's procedures. Disputes should, and do, get resolved in court, not by clerks or politicians.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Election results must be based on those certified vote totals. Rep. Andy Harris (R-MD) recently suggested North Carolina's legislature should vote to &lt;a href="https://www.politico.com/news/2024/10/25/trump-freedom-caucus-north-carolina-electors-00185520"&gt;award the state's presidential electors to candidate Donald Trump in lieu of an election&lt;/a&gt; because of potential difficulty voting following the recent hurricanes. In the 2020 election, most Republicans in Congress voted to drop the electors from Arizona and Pennsylvania out of the final count. (I know many of you believe that they voted to delay certification for an investigation, but that never happened. You won't find any vote to delay in the Congressional Record, video, or transcript.) A free and fair election requires having an election and then accepting all of its certified results once the time for court challenges is complete.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;What if the election isn't fair? You wouldn't be the first to think an election wasn't fair. I think everyone will find something about it that they don't think is fair. Or many things. But we still must conclude the election. Challenge it in court, yes. If the laws (and courts) still fail us, then we live to fight for a fairer election another day by changing the law for the next election. The paraphrased John Adams quote "a government of laws, not of men" is how we keep going. It's worked for 235 years. Refusing the result because you think it wasn't fair is not acceptable in a country of laws.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Finally, election fraud shouldn't happen either, and some may be discovered after the election. But comprehensive &lt;a href="https://apnews.com/article/voter-fraud-election-2020-joe-biden-donald-trump-7fcb6f134e528fee8237c7601db3328f"&gt;reviews of state investigations and prosecutions&lt;/a&gt; after the 2020 election, as well as reviews of prosecutions and investigations &lt;a href="https://www.nytimes.com/2024/10/28/technology/noncitizen-voting-election.html"&gt;during and before the Trump Administration&lt;/a&gt;, have shown that improper votes have not favored one party over the other, and they have numbered far fewer than the state margins that determine winners. Those ballots are also often screened-out by standard procedures before the election is over.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Let's hope for a smooth election, but now you know more about what kinds of bumps to expect and what we hope not to see.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Newly elected legislators don't take office until January 3rd at noon, so we'll be back with more updates once Congress comes back with everyone's same legislators later in November for the "&lt;a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lame_duck_(politics)#:%7E:text=Origins%20of%20the%20term,-Literally%2C%20the%20term&amp;amp;text=In%201761%2C%20Horace%20Walpole%20wrote,up%20as%20a%20lame%20duck%22."&gt;lame duck&lt;/a&gt;" session. And we may have more to say ahead of Congress's January 6 counting of presidential electors. So see you here soon.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;Correction: We originally wrote Rep. Harris was from North Carolina. He is from Maryland. Embarrassed, we apologize for the mistake.&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;      </description>
      <category>&amp;middot; Analysis and Commentary 	&amp;middot; by Joshua Tauberer 	</category>
    </item>
    <item>
      <title>Elections: A Day in the Life of an Election Worker</title>
      <author>Amy West       </author>
      <link>https://www.govtrack.us/posts/450/2024-10-28_elections-a-day-in-the-life-of-an-election-worker</link>
      <guid isPermaLink="true">https://www.govtrack.us/posts/450/2024-10-28_elections-a-day-in-the-life-of-an-election-worker</guid>
      <pubDate>Mon, 28 Oct 2024 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <description>                &lt;p&gt;On Election Day, my GovTrack hat comes off and another hat goes on: I am an election worker in Florida. This will be my fourth election. I’m the &lt;a href="https://escambiavotes.gov/election-worker-information"&gt;Equipment Operator&lt;/a&gt; for my precinct.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;This is a skilled, paid position with training before every election. This year, Florida will have had a Presidential Preference vote in March, a primary election for all other offices in August, and finally the general election in November. I will have had training three times by November 5th. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;My role starts the day before Election Day when the staff for the precinct meet at the polling place to get tables arranged, set up the voting booths, and check in with the facility staff responsible for letting us in the next morning. On the day of the election, I’m up around 4am to get back to the polling place a little before 6am. (By the way, because the polling place to which I’m assigned is not my polling place, I vote early.) &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Florida law gives the public the right to observe set up, but since 2018 when I started, no one has. The set up process is fairly rote and I’m given a checklist to make sure I do it all in the correct order and way, including: &lt;/p&gt; &lt;ul&gt; &lt;li&gt; &lt;p&gt;Unlocking &amp;amp; unsealing the part of the tabulator where the marked ballots will go and verifying there’s no marked ballots from any previous elections in there (there has never been an old ballot in there, but we still check)&lt;/p&gt; &lt;/li&gt; &lt;li&gt; &lt;p&gt;Turning on the machine&lt;/p&gt; &lt;/li&gt; &lt;li&gt; &lt;p&gt;Verifying that its count is at zero, that it has the right precinct number, date and time (it always has been right, but we always check)&lt;/p&gt; &lt;/li&gt; &lt;li&gt; &lt;p&gt;Getting the rest of the workers to review and sign the report that is automatically printed that shows the above&lt;/p&gt; &lt;/li&gt; &lt;li&gt; &lt;p&gt;Setting up the accessible voting machine&lt;/p&gt; &lt;/li&gt; &lt;/ul&gt; &lt;p&gt;The staff assigned to the ballots and check-in have their own procedures. There’s also a person called the &lt;a href="https://escambiavotes.gov/election-worker-information"&gt;Poll Deputy&lt;/a&gt; who makes sure no campaign activity takes place within 150 feet of the precinct (we’re supplied with a handy pre-measured rope), sets up directional signs, and controls the flow of voters. If it’s a nice day, that’s probably the best job because you get to spend it outside in the sun.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Then, we all take our oath of office, make sure we’ve got our badges on, and get some coffee before opening the doors at 7am sharp.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;7am to 7pm&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Each voter starts at the check-in desk. &lt;a href="https://dos.fl.gov/elections/for-voters/voting/election-day-voting/"&gt;Florida requires voters to show ID at check in&lt;/a&gt; and to verify their signature. Then they’re given a receipt that they take to the ballot table. At the ballot table they’re given their ballot in exchange for the receipt, and then they go to one of the booths to vote.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;When they’ve finished, the voter comes to my area, puts their ballot in the machine, and as soon as I hear the thunk of the ballot landing in the box and see the number increase on the screen, I thank them for voting and offer them a sticker.  My role is seeing to it that the ballots successfully run through the tabulator and get counted. If there’s a paper jam, I help clear it. If a voter gets an error message (too many choices for one contest, mismarked ballot, and similar issues), I explain the message and they can decide to cast the ballot as is, go back for a new one, or live with it not being cast at all.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;If someone wishes to use the accessible machine, the machine prints their selections. It’s basically a complicated pen. While it was initially set up with hearing and vision impaired voters in mind, anyone can use it and examples have included folks with temporary issues like forgetting to bring their reading glasses. The ballot from this machine goes into the tabulator just like all the others.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Once an hour, the clerk goes around and checks with each station to see how many check-ins there have been, how many ballots have been issued and how many tabulated. These numbers should match (and since I started they always have). That way, when 7pm rolls around, there’s no surprise.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;7pm to 8pm&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Doors close at 7pm sharp. Just as in set up, the public may observe the evening checklist. Two reports that are now printed from the tabulator are the first time we see any information other than how many ballots were cast. One goes to the Supervisor of Elections office. This copy is reviewed &amp;amp; signed by all of the precinct staff. The other copy is taped to the door of the precinct for anyone who comes by to view. This is also the only time of day that the tabulator is online. When it’s finished transmitting results to the Supervisor of Elections, it begins to shut down. Then I unseal and pull out the ballot box from the tabulator, make sure nothing’s left inside, and lock and seal the ballot box. It will go with the clerk to the Supervisor of Elections when we all leave. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Then, while the clerk does some closing paperwork, the rest of us pack and lock up all the other equipment, and about 8pm, we go home.&lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;What I want to convey is that this is a highly prescribed task. As of October 2020, &lt;a href="https://files.floridados.gov/media/703582/2020-election-code-complete.pdf"&gt;the election code was 184 pages&lt;/a&gt;. We’re not freestyling. Due to Hurricanes &lt;a href="https://www.cbsnews.com/miami/news/desantis-orders-election-changes-in-counties-hit-hard-by-helene/"&gt;Helene&lt;/a&gt; and &lt;a href="https://www.nbcmiami.com/news/local/desantis-issues-order-to-allow-election-changes-in-wake-of-hurricane-milton/3448670/"&gt;Milton&lt;/a&gt;, Gov. DeSantis has approved some modifications to rules for polling places and mail-in voting, but overall the process will still be similar in polling places throughout the state. &lt;/p&gt; &lt;p&gt;Maybe I’ll even see you on Election Day.&lt;/p&gt;      </description>
      <category>&amp;middot; Analysis and Commentary 	&amp;middot; by Amy West 	</category>
